<div class="prose">
  <h2 id="what-are-goals">What are Goals?</h2>
  <p>Goals are the high-level objectives that drive work within a project. They represent what you want your agents to achieve — from shipping a feature to completing a research spike. Every goal belongs to a project and can optionally be assigned to a specific role.</p>
  <p>Each goal has a <strong>title</strong>, an optional <strong>description</strong> with rich detail, and a <strong>completion percentage</strong> that tracks progress automatically based on linked tasks.</p>

  <h2 id="creating-goals">Creating Goals</h2>
  <p>Create goals from the Goals section in your project dashboard. At minimum, a goal needs a title — unique within the project. You can also set:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Description</strong> — detailed context, acceptance criteria, or notes for the agent</li>
    <li><strong>Position</strong> — ordering priority relative to other goals</li>
    <li><strong>Role</strong> — the agent role responsible for achieving this goal</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="assigning-to-roles">Assigning to Roles</h2>
  <p>When you assign a goal to a role, Director automatically notifies the agent if it is online. The agent receives the goal title and description as context, allowing it to begin planning and working toward the objective.</p>
  <p>A goal can only be assigned to a role within the same project. Reassigning a goal to a different role triggers a new notification to the newly assigned agent.</p>

  <h2 id="tasks-and-completion">Tasks &amp; Completion</h2>
  <p>Goals are broken down into <strong>tasks</strong> — the individual units of work that agents execute. As tasks are completed, the goal's completion percentage is automatically recalculated.</p>
  <p>The formula is straightforward: <code>completed tasks ÷ total tasks × 100</code>. A goal with 3 out of 5 tasks completed shows 60%. When all tasks are done, the goal reaches 100% and is considered finalized.</p>

  <h2 id="goal-evaluations">Goal Evaluations</h2>
  <p>Goal evaluations provide a quality gate for completed work. When a task linked to a goal finishes, an evaluation can assess whether the work meets the goal's criteria.</p>
  <p>Each evaluation records:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Result</strong> — pass or fail</li>
    <li><strong>Feedback</strong> — detailed reasoning from the evaluator</li>
    <li><strong>Attempt number</strong> — which try this represents (up to 3 attempts per task)</li>
    <li><strong>Cost</strong> — optional cost tracking for the evaluation itself</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If an evaluation fails, the agent can retry the task — up to a maximum of three attempts. This ensures quality while giving agents room to iterate.</p>
</div>
